                \n {"practice":"1","code":"SM-11","subCode":"d) verification/validation (see Clause 9, Practice 5 – Security verification and validation testing);","explanation":"The requirement mandates a structured process to ensure that security-related issues in products or patches are identified, addressed, and resolved before release. This includes rigorous verification and validation testing to confirm compliance with security standards.","context":"This practice is critical in industrial control systems (ICS) to prevent vulnerabilities from being introduced into operational environments, which could lead to security breaches or system failures.","challenges":["Complexity of ICS environments: Diverse hardware and software components make comprehensive testing difficult. Example: A PLC firmware update may behave differently across vendor-specific environments.","Legacy system compatibility: Older ICS components may not support modern security testing tools. Example: A legacy RTU may lack interfaces for automated vulnerability scanning.","Resource constraints: Limited testing resources can lead to incomplete validation. Example: A small team may prioritize functional testing over security validation.","Dynamic threat landscape: Emerging threats require continuous updates to testing methodologies. Example: A new ICS-specific malware may bypass existing validation checks.","Regulatory compliance: Meeting multiple standards (e.g., IEC 62443, NERC CIP) adds complexity. Example: A power utility must align validation processes with both IEC 62443-4-1 and NERC CIP-010."],"best_practices":[{"description":"Implement automated security testing tools tailored for ICS environments to ensure consistent validation. Example: Using specialized tools like Claroty or Nozomi Networks for ICS vulnerability scanning.","url":"https://www.claroty.com/solutions/asset-visibility-and-vulnerability-management","url_description":"Claroty's solution for ICS vulnerability management, aligne